<p>Most Central African peoples that share their habitat with apes tend to hunt them, although there are important exceptions [
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B16-viruses-04-01950">16</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B46-viruses-04-01950">46</xref>]. For the studied area, we gathered numerous references documenting the hunting of apes throughout the colonial period and beyond, both within the Boumba-Ngoko-Sangha enclosure [
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B46-viruses-04-01950">46</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B54-viruses-04-01950">54</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B55-viruses-04-01950">55</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B56-viruses-04-01950">56</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B57-viruses-04-01950">57</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B58-viruses-04-01950">58</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B59-viruses-04-01950">59</xref>], and in adjacent regions west of the Boumba [
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B46-viruses-04-01950">46</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B57-viruses-04-01950">57</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B60-viruses-04-01950">60</xref>], south of the Ngoko [
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B46-viruses-04-01950">46</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B59-viruses-04-01950">59</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B61-viruses-04-01950">61</xref>], and east of the Sangha [
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B61-viruses-04-01950">61</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B62-viruses-04-01950">62</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B63-viruses-04-01950">63</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B64-viruses-04-01950">64</xref>,
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B65-viruses-04-01950">65</xref>].
</p>
